, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1312–Abt July 1373":"circa 1312–circa juli 1373","1312–1373":"1312–1373","–1353":"–1353","1323–1413":"1323–1413","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1270–Female":"1270–Overleden","Abt July 1373":"circa juli 1373","before 1330":"vóór 1330","1373":"1373","Abt 1313":"circa 1313","Abt 1312":"circa 1312","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1413":"1413","1313":"1313","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1353":"1353","1298":"1298","about 1323":"circa 1323","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, Lancashire, England","St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1312–Abt July 1373":"about 1312–about July 1373","1312–1373":"1312–1373","–1353":"–1353","1323–1413":"1323–1413","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1270–Female":"1270–Deceased","Abt July 1373":"about July 1373","before 1330":"before 1330","1373":"1373","Abt 1313":"about 1313","Abt 1312":"about 1312","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1413":"1413","1313":"1313","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1353":"1353","1298":"1298","about 1323":"about 1323","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, Lancashire, England","St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England":"Hornby Castle, Lancashire, England","Hindley, Lancashire, England":"Hindley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Neville was born about 1312, in St Laurence in Thanet, Kent, England, United Kingdom, his father, Robert Neville, was 43 and his mother, Isabel Byron, was 43. He married Joan Atherton before 1330, in Hindley, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about July 1373, in Hindley, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 62."},"et":{"Abt 1312–Abt July 1373":"umbes 1312–umbes juuli 1373","1312–1373":"1312–1373","–1353":"–1353","1323–1413":"1323–1413","1271–1313":"1271–1313","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","Abt July 1373":"umbes juuli 1373","before 1330":"enne 1330","1373":"1373","Abt 1313":"umbes 1313","Abt 1312":"umbes 1312","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1413":"1413","1313":"1313","1323":"1323","1312":"1312","1353":"1353","1298":"1298","about 1323":"umbes 1323","Hornby, Lancashire, England":"Hornby, 